Preheat your #oven to 200°C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic_clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press). Peel and grate the @ginger{1}(peeled and grated).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the onion and fry until softened, ~{5%minutes}, stir occasionally. Add the @tomato puree{30%g}, @pasanda style seasoning{1%pack}, ginger and half the garlic. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml} and @water{450%ml}. Stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1%pinch} and bring the mixture to the boil.

Stir the @red split lentils{100%g} into the mix, then simmer the dhal until the lentils are tender, about ~{20%minutes}. Chop the @paneer{125%g} into 2cm chunks. Halve the @lime{1/2}.

> Add a splash of water if you feel it needs it while simmering.

While the dhal simmers, heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. When the oil is hot, add the paneer and fry until golden on each side, ~{5-7%minutes}, turning every 1-2 mins. Add the paneer to the pan of dhal for the rest of its cooking time.

Pop your (now empty) pan back on medium high heat with a drizzle of oil. Add the @spring greens{150%g}(sliced) with a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Stir fry until the greens are tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. In the meantime, add the @garlic and coriander naan{4} to the #oven to warm through for ~{4-5%minutes}. Once the greens are tender, add the remaining garlic to the pan and stir fry for a further ~{1%minute}. Remove the pan from the heat.

Once the dhal is cooked, remove from the heat and stir in half the spring greens. Add a squeeze of lime juice, taste and add salt, pepper and more lime juice if you feel it needs it. Spoon into #bowls{} and serve the remaining spring greens on top, the naans alongside and any remaining lime chopped into wedges. Enjoy!